summary:
Lateral and furcal accessory canals form frequently in mandibular first molars during odontogenesis through vascular influences and extend from the pulp chamber towards the furcation—an established and common anatomical variation. 

Final Answer: \boxed{C}

The primary major pattern involves lateral and furcal accessory canals arising from vascular interactions during tooth development and extending from the pulp chamber to the furcation region. These features constitute a frequent and clinically significant anatomical variant in mandibular first molars based on standard dental literature.

